.TH TREE 1 "2025" "Nightingale" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
tree \- list contents of directories in a tree-like format
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B tree
.RI [ directory ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B tree
recursively lists the contents of directories in a tree-like format,
showing the hierarchical structure of the filesystem.
.PP
The output uses ASCII art characters to show the directory structure:
.IP \(bu 3
.B +-
marks each entry
.IP \(bu
.B |
shows vertical continuation
.IP \(bu
Symlinks are shown with
.B ->
followed by their target in red
.PP
If no directory is specified, the current directory is used.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B tree
Display the tree structure of the current directory.
.TP
.B tree /bin
Show all files under /bin in tree format.
.TP
.B tree /
Display the entire filesystem as a tree.
.SH NOTES
Unlike the traditional Unix
.BR tree
command, this version:
.IP \(bu 3
Does not support filtering options
.IP \(bu
Does not print size information
.IP \(bu
Always recurses fully (no depth limit option)
.IP \(bu
Uses ANSI color codes for symlinks
